# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cef-embedded
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cef-embedded/blink-browser-engine] To create Chrome, Google initially chose to use Apple's WebKit engine.
[src:cef-embedded/blink-browser-engine] However, Google needed to make substantial changes to its code to support Chrome's novel multi-process browser architecture.
[src:cef-embedded/blink-browser-engine] Over the course of several years, the divergence from Apple's version increased, so Google decided to officially fork its version as Blink in 2013.
[src:cef-embedded/blink-browser-engine] Blink's name was influenced by two factors: the implication of speed, and a reference to the non-standard blink HTML element, popularised by Netscape Navigator, but which was never actually implemented within Blink.
[src:cef-embedded/blink-browser-engine] By commit count, Google was the largest contributor to the WebKit project from late 2009 until the fork in 2013.
[src:cef-embedded/blink-browser-engine] One of the first changes of the new fork was to deprecate CSS vendor prefixes, including WebKit's; experimental Blink functionality is instead enabled on an opt-in basis.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] The **Chromium Embedded Framework** (**CEF**) is an open-source software framework for embedding a Chromium web browser within another application.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] This enables developers to add web browsing functionality to their application, as well as the ability to use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript to create the application's user interface (or just portions of it).
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] It has many language bindings including C, C++, Go, Java, and Python.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] There are two versions of Chromium Embedded Framework: CEF 1 and CEF 3.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] Development of CEF 2 was abandoned after the appearance of the Chromium Content API.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] CEF 1 is a single-process implementation based on the Chromium WebKit API.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] It is no longer actively developed or supported.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] CEF 3 is a multi-process implementation based on the Chromium Content API and has performance similar to Google Chrome.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] It uses asynchronous messaging to communicate between the main application process and one or more render processes (Blink + V8 JavaScript engine).
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] As of July 2022, it no longer supports PPAPI plugins due to removal of PPAPI, legacy Chrome Apps, and Native Client (NaCl) support from the upstream Chromium project.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] PDF viewer support from Chromium's PDFium PDF viewer is still supported.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] The single-process run mode is not supported, but still present; currently is being used for debugging purposes only.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] Both of these releases were based on Chromium 73.0.3683.75, however the new version numbering has the major number the same as the Chromium major version number it is based on.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] CEF comes with a sample application called CefClient that is written in C++ using WinAPI, Cocoa, or GTK (depending on the platform) and contains demos of various features.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] Newer versions include a sample application called CefSimple that, along with an accompanying tutorial, show how to create a simple application using CEF 3.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-embedded-framework] Documentation can be found in the header files located in the "include" directory and on wiki pages.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Chromium is a free and open-source software project.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Owing to its origins in the WebKit project, Chromium incorporates code subject to a variety of licenses, including LGPL, MIT, Ms-PL, and MPL (with the MPL/GPL/LGPL tri-license clause).
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Original Google-authored portions and some portions written by Apple are shared under the 3-clause BSD license.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] This licensing permits any party to build the codebase and share the resulting browser executable with the Chromium name and logo.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Thus many Linux distributions do this, as well as FreeBSD and OpenBSD.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Chromium also forms the basis of Electron, which in turn is used for many commercial and proprietary cross-platform applications, such as Slack.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Many Chromium-based browsers, such as Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge, include the proprietary components, such as proprietary wrapper libraries for hardware acceleration.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Chromium provides the vast majority of source code for Google Chrome, but there are important differences.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Google first chose the name "Chrome" with intention to minimize *chrome* for its browser.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Then the open-source release was named "Chromium" because chromium metal is used to make chrome plating.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Chrome has the same user interface functionality as Chromium, but with a Google-branded color scheme.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Unlike Chromium, Chrome is not open-source; its binaries are licensed as freeware under the Google Chrome Terms of Service.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The Chromium browser codebase contains over 36 million source lines of code, excluding comments and blank lines.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Chromium has been a Google project since its inception, and Google employees have done the bulk of the development work.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Google refers to this project and the offshoot ChromiumOS as "the Chromium projects", and its employees use @chromium.org email addresses for this development work.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] However, in terms of governance, the Chromium projects are not independent entities; Google retains firm control of them.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The Chromium browser codebase is widely used, so others have made important contributions, most notably Microsoft, Avast, Igalia, Yandex, Intel, Samsung, LG, Opera, Vivaldi, and Brave.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Some employees of these companies also have @chromium.org email addresses.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Google designed the first multi-process browser.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Compared to single-process designs, this architecture has better responsiveness with many browser tabs open and security benefits of process isolation, but with the trade-off of higher memory usage.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] This was later refined as per-process website isolation, providing additional security.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Another important design decision was for the browser's user interface to be minimalistic.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The browser engine was originally based on Apple's WebKit, which Google deemed the "obvious choice" of available options.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] However, Google's novel multi-process design required engine changes.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] This divergence from Apple's version increased over time, so in 2013 Google officially forked its version as the Blink engine.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] However, as of 2025, Google is still working on getting the Blink engine onto iOS, and has released experimental code for it.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] C++ is the primary language, comprising over half of the codebase.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] This includes the Blink and V8 engines, the implementation of HTTP and other protocols, the internal caching system, the extension API, and most of the user interface.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The rest of the user interface, called the WebUI, is implemented in HTML, CSS, and JavaScript (usually via TypeScript transpilation).
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] An extensive collection of web platform tests is also written in these languages plus XML.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Third-party libraries that provide essential functionality, such as SQLite and numerous codecs, are written in C, C++, or beginning in 2023, the newer Rust language.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Support for mobile operating systems requires special languages: for Android both Java and Kotlin, and for iOS both Objective-C and Swift.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Python is the main language of the build system, which also has special configuration files for Google's GN tool.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The bug tracking system is a publicly accessible website.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Participants are identified by their email addresses.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The Chromium continuous integration system automatically builds and tests the codebase several times a day.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Builds are identified by a four-part version number that is major.minor.build.patch.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] This versioning scheme and the branch points that occur every six to seven weeks are from Google Chrome and its development cycle.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Google Chrome debuted in September 2008, and along with its release, the Chromium source code was also made available, allowing builds to be constructed from it.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Upon release, Chrome was criticized for storing a user's passwords without the protection of a master password.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Google has insisted that a master password provides no real security against knowledgeable hackers, but users argued that it would protect against co-workers or family members borrowing a computer and being able to view stored passwords as plaintext.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Kasting stated: "A master password was issue 1397.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] We will not implement a master password.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] 'A bunch of people would like it' won't make it happen.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Our design decisions are not democratic.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Version 3 was the first alpha available for Linux.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Chromium soon incorporated native theming for Linux, using the GTK+ toolkit to allow it fit into the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Version 3 also introduced JavaScript engine optimizations and user-selectable themes.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Version 6 introduced features for user interface minimalism, as one of Google's goals was to make the browser "feel lightweight (cognitively and physically) and fast".
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The changes were a unified tools menu, no home button by default (although user configurable), a combined reload/stop button, and the bookmark bar deactivated by default.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] It also introduced an integrated PDF reader, WebM and VP8 support for use with HTML video, and a smarter URL bar.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Version 7 boosted performance to twice that of prior versions via hardware acceleration.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Version 8 focused on improved integration into ChromeOS and improved cloud features.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] These include background web applications, host remoting (allowing users centrally to control features and settings on other computers) and cloud printing.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Version 9 introduced a number of features, including a URL bar feature for exposing phishing attacks and sandboxing for the Adobe Flash plug-in.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Other additions were the WebGL library and access for the new Chrome Web Store.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] In February, Google announced that it was considering large-scale user interface (UI) changes, including at least partial elimination of the URL bar, which had been a mainstay of browsers since the early years of the Web.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The proposed UI was to be a consolidation of the row of tabs and the row of navigation buttons, the menu, and URL bar into a single row.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The justification was freeing up more screen space for web page content.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Google acknowledged that this would result in URLs not always being visible to the user, that navigation controls and menus may lose their context, and that the resulting single line could be quite crowded.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] However, by August, Google decided that these changes were too risky and shelved the idea.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] In March, Google announced other directions for the project.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Development priorities focused on reducing the size of the executable, integrating web applications and plug-ins, cloud computing, and touch interface support.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Thus a multi-profile button was introduced to the UI, allowing users to log into multiple Google and other accounts in the same browser instance.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Other additions were malware detection and support for hardware-accelerated CSS transforms.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] By May, the results of Google's attempts to reduce the file size of Chromium were already being noted.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Much of the early work in this area concentrated on shrinking the size of WebKit, the image resizer, and the Android build system.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Subsequent work introduced a more compact mobile version that reduced the vertical space of the UI.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Other changes in 2011 were GPU acceleration on all pages, adding support for the new Web Audio API, and the Google Native Client (NaCl) which permits native code supplied by third parties as platform-neutral binaries to be securely executed within the browser itself.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Google's Skia graphics library was also made available for all Chromium versions.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The sync service added for Google Chrome in 2012 could also be used by Chromium builds.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The same year, a new API for high-quality video and audio communication was added, enabling web applications to access the user's webcam and microphone after asking permission to do so.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Then GPU accelerated video decoding for Windows and support for the QUIC protocol were added.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] In 2013, Chromium's modified WebKit rendering engine was officially forked as the Blink engine.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Other changes in 2013 were the ability to reset user profiles and new browser extension APIs.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Tab indicators for audio and webcam usage were also added, as was automatic blocking of files detected as malware.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Version 67 added the security benefit of per-process website isolation.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Then version 69 introduced a new browser theme, as part of the tenth anniversary of Google Chrome.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] The same year, new measures were added to curtail abusive advertising.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Since 2021, the Google Chrome sync service can no longer be used by Chromium builds.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Also, starting with version 89, only Intel and AMD processors with the SSE3 instruction set or later are supported.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Starting with version 110, only Windows 10 and later are supported for Windows users.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] In addition to Google Chrome, Microsoft Edge, Opera, Vivaldi and Brave, many other actively developed browsers are based on the Chromium code.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Most of these are proprietary, like Chrome, but some remain free and open-source software (FOSS), like Chromium.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] With either approach, the custom app is implemented with HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and other web technologies.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Moreover, the app can be readily deployed on the operating systems supported by Chromium.
[src:cef-embedded/chromium-web-browser] Since the 2010s, many apps have been created this way.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] In computer science, **interprocess communication** (**IPC**) is the sharing of data between running processes in a computer system, or between multiple such systems.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] Mechanisms for IPC may be provided by an operating system.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] Applications which use IPC are often categorized as clients and servers, where the client requests data and the server responds to client requests.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] Many applications are both clients and servers, as commonly seen in distributed computing.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] IPC is very important to the design process for microkernels and nanokernels, which reduce the number of functionalities provided by the kernel.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] Those functionalities are then obtained by communicating with servers via IPC, leading to a large increase in communication when compared to a regular monolithic kernel.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] IPC interfaces generally encompass variable analytic framework structures.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] These processes ensure compatibility between the multi-vector protocols upon which IPC models rely.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] An IPC mechanism is either synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] Synchronization primitives may be used to have synchronous behavior with an asynchronous IPC mechanism.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] Merging data from two processes can often incur significantly higher costs compared to processing the same data on a single thread, potentially by two or more orders of magnitude due to overheads such as inter-process communication and synchronization.
[src:cef-embedded/inter-process-communication] Different approaches to IPC have been tailored to different software requirements, such as performance, modularity, and system circumstances such as network bandwidth and latency.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:cef-embedded/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
[src:cef-embedded/webview] A **WebView** is a web browser that is embedded within an app.
[src:cef-embedded/webview] Thus, a WebView is a large-scale software component that enables the use of web content within apps.
[src:cef-embedded/webview] In some cases, the entire functionality of the app is implemented this way.
[src:cef-embedded/webview] Other examples are Microsoft's legacy WebView, based on its deprecated EdgeHTML and MSHTML engines, and the WebView component in JavaFX.
